eng: an Sinus be Cured? “Sinus I nfections Signs and Symptoms”  Sinusitis is an inflammation of the membrane lining of any sinus, especially one of the paranasal sinuses. Actite sinusitis is 2 short-term condition that responds well to antibiotics and decongestants; chronic sinusits is characterized by at least four recurrences of acute sinusitis. Either medication or surgery s a possible treatment.  For acute sinusitis, symptoms include facial pain/pressure, nasal obstruction, nasal discharge, diminished sense of smell, and cough not due to asthma (in children). Additionally, sufferers of this disorder could incur fever, bad breath, fatigue, dental pain, and cough.  Acute sinusitis can last four weeks or more. This condition may be present when the patient has two or more symptoms and/or the presence of thick, green or yellow nasal discharge. Actite bacterial infection might be present when symptoms worsen after five days, persist after ten days, or the severity of symptoms is out of proportion to those normally associated with a viral infection.  Acute sinusi     is generally treated with ten to 14 days of antibiotic care. With treatment, the symptoms disappear, and antibiotics are no longer required for that episode. However, the sinusitis will probably return, and the antibiotics will have weakened your immune system. Oral and topical decongestants also may be prescribed to alleviate the symptoms. These too will have a negative effect on your immune system.  Victims of chronic sinusitis may have the following symptoms for 12 weeks or more: facial pain/pressure, facial congestion/fullness, nasal obstruction /blockage, thick nasal discharge/discolored post-nasal drainage, pus in the nasal cavity, and at times, fever. They may also have headache, bad breath, and fatigue.  Warm moist     ir may alleviate sinus congestion. Experts recommend a vaporizer or steam from a pan of boiled water (removed from the heat). Humidifiers should be used only when a clean filter is in place to preclude spraying bacteria or fungal spores into the air. Warm compresses are useful in relieving pain in the nose and sinuses. Saline nose drops are also helpful in moisturizing nasal passages. The latest sinus infection discovery is now also widely available.

eng: HOME REMEDIES —T0 TREAT—     WHAT IS WHEEZING?  ‘Wheezing is when you are unable to breathe properly. Air is passing into the lungs and is being exhaled as well, but the process is not smooth and efficient. Wheezing happens when there is a blockage that impedes the flow of air in and out of the lungs.  Garlic is very useful in treating breathing difficulties and removing the wheezing sound. It has amazing anti-oxidant and anti-inflammatory properties. Its antibiotic action takes care of the viral infection, reducing the inflammation and clearing the congestion in the lungs.     Ginger is a popular natural treatment for various illnesses including asthma. It is known to reduce respiratory tract inflammation and inhibit its contraction.     The nutritive properties of figs encourage respiratory health and help remove phlegm and reduce breathing difficulties.  ‘Wash three dried figs and soak them in a cup of water overnight. In the morning, eat the soaked figs and drink the fig water on an empty stomach.     Try and eat raw onions with all your meals. The sulfur present in compounds found in onions contains antimicrobial elements that combat all kinds of infections. Onions are helpful against wheezing, and also against colds and coughs. eng: Drug Facts  Active ingredient (in each tablet) Purpose Cetirizine HCI 10 mg.... Antihistamine     Uses temporarily relieves these symptoms due to hay fever or other upper respiratory allergies: mrunnynose Msneezing M itchy, watery eyes M itching of the nose or throat  Warnings Do not use if you have ever had an allergic reaction to this product or any of its ingredients or to an antihistamine containing hydroxyzine.  Ask a doctor before use if you have liver or kidney disease. Your doctor should determine if you need a different dose. Ask a doctor or pharmacist before use if you are taking tranquilizers or sedatives.  When using this product  m drowsiness may occur M avoid alcoholic drinks  m alcohol, sedatives, and tranquilizers may increase drowsiness W be careful when driving a motor vehicle or operating machinery  Stop use and ask a doctor if an allergic reaction to this product occurs. Seek medical help right away. If pregnant or breast-feeding:                 m if breast-feeding: not recommended M if pregnant: ask a health professional before use. Keep out of reach of children. In case of overdose, get medical help or contact a Poison Control Center right away. (1-800-222-1222)  Directions  adults and children one 10 mg tablet once daily; do not take more than one 10 mg tablet in 6 years and over 24 hours. A 5 mg product may be appropriate for less severe symptoms.  adults 65 years and over ask a doctor children under 6 years of age ask a doctor  consumers with liver ask a doctor or kidney disease                 Other information m store between 20-25°C (68-77°F)  Inactive ingredients corn starch, FD&C blue no. 1 aluminum lake, hypromellose, lactose monohydrate, magnesium stearate, polydextrose, polyethylene glycol, povidone, titanium dioxide, triacetin  Questions or comments?1-800-719-9260

eng: Overcoming  SEASONAL AM,ERGMES  EIIE:1]Y  FOODS TO AVOID  Alcohol Artificial sweeteners Shellfish  Caffeine Processed foods Bottled citrus juice Conventional dairy Melons Echinacea Chocolate Bananas Chamonmile Peanuts Cucumbers Wheat  Sugar Sunflower seeds 1l  FOODS TO ENJOY  RAW LOCAL HONEY  Relieves symptoms because it contains local pollen that is causing your allergies. Take a couple of tablespoons each day.  HOT AND SPICY FOODS  Thins the mucus, and allow it to be more easily expressed. Try adding garlic, onion, ginger, cinnamon and cayenne pepper to your recipes.  BONE BROTH  Bone broth, from chicken, beef or lamb, helps to ease respiratory problems, and help to expel excess nasal mucus.  PROBIOTIC-RICH FOODS  Support a stronger immune system, improve digestion, increase energy levels, and so much more. Eat kefir, sauerkraut or kimchi, kombucha, natto, yogurt and raw cheese.  PINEAPPLE  The enzyme Bromelain found in pineapple in addition to high levels of vitamins B, C and other essential nutrients can help to reduce your reaction to seasonal allergies.  APPLE CIDER VINEGAR  Helps to boost the immune system, helps to break up mucus and supports lymphatic drainage. Three times per day, mix 1 tablespoon of ACV with  1 tablespoon of fresh-squeezed lemon juice, and % tablespoon of local raw honey and drink.  FRESH ORGANIC VEGETABLES Include Swiss chard (that is high in quercetin), cabbage, beets, carrots and yams to help you fight seasonal allergies.  CLEAN PROTEINS  Consume grass-fed meats, free-range poultry and wild-caught fish to provide the right vitamins, omega-3s, essential minerals and protein to boost your immunity.  plements to Help e Allergy Fight  Spirulina - 1 teaspoon per day  Stops the release of histamine that causes symptoms.  Quercetin - 1000 mg per day  The flavonoid that gives fruits and vegetables their rich color, quercetin stops the production and release of histamine.  Butterbur - 500 mg per day Traditionally used to treat bronchitis, excess mucus and asthma, it was found to be as effective as Zyrtec/Allegra for  treating hay fever. (However, young children, pregnant or breastfeeding women should not take butterbur supplements.)  Probiotics - 50 billion IU (2-6 capsules) per day Modifies the intestinal flora in the gut improving immune  system and shows promise in the treatment and prevention of allergies.  Vitamin A - 2000 mcg per day  Boosts the immune system, fights inflammation and has antihistamine properties.  Bromelain - 1,000 mg per day  The enzyme in pineapple helps to reduce swelling in the nose and sinuses, helping to relieve hay fever symptoms.  Zinc - 30 mg per day  Helps to heal adrenal fatigue caused by chronic stress, as stress worsens the symptoms of seasonal allergies.  Stinging Nettle - 300-500 mg twice per day  o e e R R T T ey ety help to reduce the body’s production of symptom causing histamine.     Dr. Axe  R

Cough-Variant Asthma (CVA)  While cough may accompany the usual symptoms associated with asthma, in CVA, cough alone may be a precursor to or the sole symptom. When cough is the only symptom, this is known as cough variant  asthma (CVA). What is Cough Variant Asthma2  The main symptom ofCVA is a chronic, non-productive cough. These asthma patients have cough as the maln or only symptom of their asthma. These patients are a small percentage of total asthma patients:. CVA patients are, however, a distinct group rather than merely being thought ofas coughing asthmatics.  CVA patients have some differences from patients with typical asthma. For example, while normal asthmatics do not differ from healthy volunteers in their cough relex, CVA patients have a more sensitive  COugh reflex.  How Is Cough Variant Asthma Diagnosed2  Cough-variant asthma is somewhat difficult to diagnose because the cough may be the only symptom, and the cough itself may appear to be bronchitis or a cough associated with postnasal drip. Your doctor will ask you questions about your medical history and will examine you and listen to you breathe. However, people with CVA often have normal physical examinations, chest X- ra义′ peak flow  Imeasurements and spirometry.     Spirometry involyes measuring how much air you can exhale after first taking a deep breath, and how quickly you can empty your Iungs. A final test may be a Methacholine challenge test to evaluate for asthma, but itmay require the use ofa special facility. This test may be performed if your symptoms and spirometry test do not clearly show asthma. Interestingly, CVA patients have a smaller reaction to methacholine challenge testing compared to other asthmatics.  How Is Cough Variant Asthma Treated?2 `  Treatment orCVA is virtually the same as for asthma. Partial improvement of Chronic cough may be  Seen as quickly as 1 week with bronchodilators like Albuterol but may not completely resolye for up to 8 weeks after starting an inhaled steroid like Flovent.  Ifthe cough only partially resolves, your provider may try a more potent steroid like oral prednisone. Alternatively, your provider may do special tests to identif〉 eosinophils or feno, a marker of inflammation, in your lung. eng: PR R e  Original Article  hitps:/d0i0rg/10.5415/apallergy2017.7.3.148 Asa Pac Allergy 2017,7:148-155  A review of 42 asthmatic children with allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis  ‘Ashok Shah* and Shekhar Kunal  Department o Pulmonary Medicine, Vallabhbha Patel Chest Institute, University of Delh, Delhi 110007, India     Background: Allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis (ABPA) in children with asthma, not associated with cystic fibrosis, is yet to receive the recogntion it deserves  Objective: To highlight the presentation of ABPA in children with asthrma,  Methods: This retrospective review documents the occurrence of pediaric ABPA over a period of 31 years in one unit. Children with asthma, eosinophilia and infiltrates on chest radiograph were screened for ABPA. In these patients, demonstration of immediate hypersensitivty response against Aspergils species along with serological profle and pulmonary function testing were done. eng: nal Article     IEIS] cinicat s speriment Oubinolamgios 2016 by 21 Eubaesdof i  @~  it doiorg/1021083/ce0.2016.00220 PISSN 1976-8710 lSSN 2005-0720  The Effectiveness of Budesonide Nasal Irrigation After Endoscopic Sinus Surgery in Chronic Rhinosinusitis With Asthma  Tae Wook Kang - Jae Ho Chung - Seok Hyun Cho - Seung Hwan Lee - Kyung Rae Kim - Jin Hyeok Jeong  Department of Otolaryngology-Head and Neck Surgers; Hanyang University School of Medicine, Seoud, Korea  ‘Objectives. Budesonide nasal irrigation was introduced recently for postoperative management of patients with chronic rh- inosinusiti. The safety and therapeutic effectiveness of this procedure is becoming accepted by many physicians. The objective of this study was to evaluate the efficacy of postoperative steroid irrigation in patients with chronic rhinosi-  nusitis and asthma,  Methods. This prospective study involved 12 chronic thinosinusitis patients with nasal polyps and asthma who received oral steroid treatment for recurring or worsening disease. The 22-item Sinonasal Outcomes Test (SNOT-22) and Lund- Kennedy endoscopy scores were checked before nasal budesonide irrigation, and 1, 2, 4, and 6 months after irriga- tion. We also calculated the total amount of oral steroids and inhaled steroids in the 6 months before irrgation and  the 6 months after .  Results. The mean SNOT-22 score improved from 30.8414.4 before irrigation to 14.2£8.7 after 6 months of irrigation (P=0.030).The endoscopy score also improved from 7.4:4.7 before irrigation to 2.2:+2.7 after 6 months (P<0.001). ‘The total amount of oral steroid was decreased from 397.897.6 mg over the 6 months before irrigation to 72.7+  99.7 mg over the 6 months after irrigation (P<0.001).  Conelusion. Nasal irrigation with budesonide i an effective postoperative treatment for chronic rhinosinusits with asthma,  which recurs frequently, reducing the oral steroid intake. Keywords. Nasal Lavage; Budesonide; Sinusitis; Asthma; Nasal Polyp.  INTRODUCTION  Chronic thinosinusitis (CRS) with nasal polyp is a common in- flammatory condition of the nasal mucosa carrying significant ‘morbidity and detriment to quality of life (QOL). Many CRS patients with nasal polyps require surgery. Along with the devel- opment of new equipment and technology, the resolution of the endoscope has increased resulting in a decrease in recurtence of  *Received February 1,2016 Revised May 3,2016 Accepted May 30,2016  « Cormespanding author: Jin Hyeok Jeong. Department of Otolaryngology-Head and Neck Sorgery, Hanyang University School of Medicine, 222 Wangsimn 1o, Seongdong g5, Seoul 04763, Korea Tl +52.31.560.2368, Fax: +82.31.560.2894 Email: ent@hanyang s ke  the discase. Unfortunately, even after surgery the patients with asthma are often difficult to manage because of the high recur rence rate and worse clinical course. We have to explain to pa- tients with asthma before the surgery that endoscopic sinus sur- gery (ESS) is not intended to be curative but s rather directed towards long-term symptom control 1] The current mainstay of medical therapy for CRS with asthma after surgery is saline iri- gation, topical or systemic steroid or recurrent oral medication of some other kind. That's Allergy & Asthma Associates of Southern California - because we're your friends and neighbors, too.  Our practice was founded in 1980 by Dr. William E. Berger. Today, along with his partner Dr. Warner W. Carr, and their outstanding team of physicians, Dr. Mark S. Sugar and Dr. Christina D. Schwindt, they provide exceptional allergy and asthma care for children and adults. Giving exceptional support to the doctors are our certified physician assistants, April N. Showalter and Sumit K. Singh, each of whom shares this practice goal. Together we’ve helped thousands of children and adults find welcome relief from allergies, asthma, sinus problems and other related conditions. It's just one of many reasons why our current patients refer more than half of our new patients.  Another reason is that our doctors have established themselves as leaders in the field of allergy and asthma care. Through our Southern California Research Center, they have conducted leading-edge research and clinical trials for some of the largest pharmaceutical companies in the world. In addition, they've lectured across the country and held prominent positions in professional medical associations and top medical schools. Their efforts will help improve patient care for years to come.  Allergy & Asthma Associates of Southern California provides state-of-the-art diagnostic allergy testing and relief from the symptoms of seasonal allergies, sinus allergies, skin allergies, food allergies, gluten allergies, chronic sinusitis, asthma, exercise-induced asthma and pediatric asthma. Common symptoms may include difficulty breathing, runny nose, watery eyes, wheezing and chronic cough. We provide leading-edge treatments, including immunotherapy, for seasonal allergies, gluten allergies, sinus allergies, skin allergies and food allergies.  Together our team of doctors and staff specialize in allergy and immunology in southern Orange County, California, providing diagnosis and treatment for all types of allergies, asthma and skin conditions such as eczema.  Patients like the fact that our doctors and staff treat them just like family. Even children appreciate our friendly, unhurried and informative care because we make children’s allergy testing visits fun and positive experiences. Thanks to our highly specialized care, we can help you improve your health and quality of life right here in Mission Viejo, Irvine and San Clemente. We also serve the Orange County (OC), CA communities of Aliso Viejo, Coto de Caza, Dana Point, Ladera Ranch, Laguna Beach, Laguna Hills, Laguna Niguel, Lake Forest, Newport Beach, Rancho Santa Margarita, San Juan Capistrano and Talega.  Call (949) 364-2900 to schedule your appointment today with one of our allergy and asthma doctors. You can also use our online Request an Appointment form to schedule a future date and time. eng: 185  Perspective  Chronic Sinusitis: Relationship Between CT Findings and Clinical History of Asthma, Allergy, Eosinophilia, and Infection  C. Douglas Phillips’ and Thomas A. E. Platts-Mills?  An interdisciplinary study from the University of Virginia was. reported in a recent issue of the Journal o the American Medical Assaciation (JAMA) (1]. The results of that study are pertinent to radiologists who interpret CT scans for patients with chronic sinus disease. The study examined the relationship among ‘eosinophilia, asthma, allergy, and sinusitis and assessed the findings obtained for the paranasal sinuses by high-resolution CT. Softtissue disease seen within the paranasal sinuses on CT scans is often described 8s mucosal thickening or mucopert- osteal thickening, with itie atiention t0 its exact nature. The JAMA article showed that for patients properly prepared for sinus CT, the thickened mucosa depicted within the sinonasal cavty is a significant site of functional, immunologically active tissue. The purpose of this artcle is to bring the findings of the JAMA report 1o the attention of radiologists and to emphasize the imaging technique, findings, and clinical relevance of the resuts.     Results of the JAMA Study  Chronic symptoms involving the sinuses are one of the most common reasons for patients to consult physicians in the United States. The incidence of allergic disease in gen- eral is thought to be increasing. Overall,data from the JAMA study (1] suggest that the relationship among eosinophila, asthma, allergy. and sinusits is significant only in patients with extensive sinus disease, as depicted by CT (Table 1; Figs. 1 and 2). Allergic subjects are fikely to have significant and extensive sinus disease, reflected on CT scans as mucosal thickening. Whatis the nature of this association? In the JAMA study, extensive disease correlated strongly with  Foceived May 3. 1994; acooped afer revision August 9, 1994.           the presence of immunoglobuiin E (IgE) antibodies to com- mon inhalant allergens. Conversely, the prevalence of IgE antibodies was low in patients with imited disease. However, a simple IgE-mediated mechanism for extensive sinus dis- ease is unlikely, because extensive disease did not correlate with total serum levels of IgE. The most striking association was between peripheral eosinophilia and extensive sinus disease (Table 1). This strong correlation was noted across the groups of patients, even among patients without a history of wheezing and among nonallergic (radioallergosorbent test-negative) patients. This result suggests that inflamma- tion in the sinus tissue may be the source of the interleukin-5. production that gives fise to eosinophilia. Whether the aero- bic bacteria in the sinus tissue can be a source of antigen- stimulating T-cells at ths site is an important question and represents another potential area of clinical investigation. MR imaging has not yet displayed the key interfaces at the lateral nasal wallor the ostiomeatal complex ciearly enough to allow ts use for routine screening, but it still has a role in the examination of patients with complications of chronic sinusits, and it has been used in other studies (2], CT seems 10 be the ideal tool for evaluating sinus changes and sinus disease that is not responsive to medical management. It provides adequate resolution of the nasal cavity and sinuses. is sensitive 1o the extent and location of mucosal disease, is widely available, and is easily quantiied for analysis. How- ever, for the depicted mucosal abnormliies in patients with sinus disease 1o be viewed as significant, screening sinus CT should be preceded by adequate medical preparation. spa: 185  Perspective  Chronic Sinusitis: Relationship Between CT Findings and Clinical History of Asthma, Allergy, Eosinophilia, and Infection  C. Douglas Phillips' and Thomas A. E. Platts-Mills?  An interdisciplinary study from the University of Virginia was reported in a recent issue of the Joumal of the American Medical Association (JAMA) (1]. The results ofthat study are pertinent to radiologists who interpret CT scans for patients with chronic sinus disease. The study examined the relationship among eosinophila, asthma, allergy, and sinusitis and assessed the findings obtalned for the paranasal sinuses by high-resolution T. Soft-issue disease seen within the paranasal sinuses on CT scans is often described as mucosal thickening or mucoperi- osteal thickening, with lítie attention to íts exact nature. The JAMA artiie showed that for patients properly prepared for sinus CT, the thickened mucosa depicted within the sinonasal cavi is a significant site o functional, immunologically active tissue. The purpose of this artcie is to bring the fndings of the JAMA report 10 the attention of radiologists and to emphasize the imaging technique, findings, and clinical relevance of the results.     Results of the JAMA Study  Chronic symptoms involving the sinuses are one of the most common reasons for patients to consult physicians in the United States. The incidence of allergic disease in gen- eral is thought to be increasing. Overal, data from the JAMA study [1] suggest that the relationship among eosinophilia, asthma, allergy, and sinusitis is significant only in patients with extensive sinus disease, as depicted by CT (Table 1; Figs. 1 and 2). Allrgic subjects are likely to have significant and extensive sinus disease, reflected on CT scans as mucosal thickening. Whatis the nature f this association? In the JAMA study, extensive disease correlated strongly with  Received May 3.1994: accepted aferrviion Augusl 9 1994.           the presence of immunoglobulin E (19E) antibodies to com- mon inhalant allergens. Conversely, the prevalence of IgE antibodies was lowin patients wilh límited disease. However, a simple IgE-mediated mechanism for extensive sínus dis- ease is unlikely, because extensive disease did not correlate wih total serum levels of IgE. The most striking association was between peripheral eosinophilia and extensive sinus disease (Table 1). This strong corelation was noted across he groups of patients, even among patients without a history of wheezing and among nonallergic (radicallergosorbent test-negative) patients. This result suggests that inflamma- tion in the sinus tissue may be the source of the interleukin-5 production that gives rise to eosinophilia. Whether the aero- bic bactería in the sinus tíssue can be a source of antigen- simulating T-cells at this site is an important question and represents another potential area of ciinical investigation. MR imaging has not yet displayed the key interfaces at the lateral nasal wallor the ostiomeatal complex clearly enough 10 allow ts use for routine screening, but it stil has a role ín the examination of patients ith complications of chronic sinusits, and it has been used in other studies [2). CT seems 10 be the ideal tool for evaluating sinus changes and sinus disease that is not responsive to medical management. It provides adequate resolution of the nasal cavity and sinuses, 1s sensitive to the extent and location of mucosal disease, is widely available, and is easily quantfied for analysis. How- ever, for the depicted mucosal abnormaliies in patients with sinus disease to be viewed as significant, screening sinus T should be preceded by adequate mecical preparation           Depariment ol Radiiogy, Box 170, Unersty o Vrinia Healh Sclences Center, Chartesile, VA 22908. Results from the Global Allergy and Asthma Network of Excellence (GAZLEN) Survey  Vanessa Garcia-Larsen''”"®, Rhonda Arthur?, James F. Potts', Peter H. Howarth?, Matti Ahlstrém”,  Tari Haahtela*, Carlos Loureiro®, Ana Todo Bom®, Grzegorz Brozek®, Joanna Makowska’, Marek L. Kowalski”, Trine Thilsing®, Thomas Keil®'?, Paolo M. Matricardi'", Kjell Torén'?, Thibaut van Zele'?, Claus Bachert Barbara Rymarczyk'®, Christer Janson'®, Bertil Forsberg'”, Ewa Nizankowska-Mogilnicka'®  and Peter G. J. Bumey’     Abstract  Background: Fuits and vegetables are rich in compounds with proposed antioxidant, anti-allergic and antinflam- matory properties, which could contribute to reduce the prevalence of asthma and allergic diseases.  Obijective: We investigated the association between asthma, and chronic rhino-sinusitis (CRS) with intake of fruits and vegetables in European aduls.  Methods: A stratified random sample was drawn from the Giobal Allergy and Asthma Network of Excellence (GAZLEN) screening survey, in which 55,000 adults aged 15-75 answered a questionnaire on respiratory symptoms. Asthma score (derived fiom self-reported asthma symptoms) and CRS were the outcomes of interest. Dietary intake of 22 subgroups of fuits and vegetables was ascertained using the internationally validated GA?LEN Food Frequency Questionnaire. Adjusted associations were examined with negative binomial and multiple regressions. Simes proce dure was used to control for multiple testing  Results: A total of 3206 individuals had valid data on asthma and dietary exposures of interest, 22.8% reported hay- ing at least 1 asthma symptom (asthma score 1), whilst 19.5% had CRS. After adjustment for potential confounders, asthma score was negatively associated with intake of dried frus (B-coefficient —2.34; 95% confidence interval [C1 —4.09, ~0559), whilst CRS was statistically negatively associated with total intake of fruits (OR 0.73; 95% C1 055, 0.97). Conversely, a positive association was observed between asthma score and aliums vegetables (adjusted B-coefficient 0.23; 95% C1 006, 040). None of these associations remained statistically significant after controling for multiple testing,  Conclusion and clinical relevance: There was no consistent evidence for an association of asthma or CRS with fruit and vegetable intake in this representative sample of European adults  Keywords: Fruits, Vegetables, Asthma, Chronic rhino-sinusitis, Adults, Europe, Meta-analysis, GAZLEN        “Conespondence: vaaaanenmperalac ¥ Respiratory Epidemmiology, Occupationl Mecicine and Public Healh Group,National Heartand Lung Insttte mperal Colege London, Emmanuel Kaye Bulding.Manvesa Rosd London SW3 6L8, UK  Full It o auhor information s avalabe at the end of thearice        ) e Aot 2017 T e it e s o he e Comons tton 40 e i oA A o P St S oy b o e et e     nd nccate hanges were made.Th Cistve Commons publecomainzero ) spples o the data mace avalabe

Howarth?, Matti Ahistróm,  Tari Haahtela*, Carlos Loureiro”, Ana Todo Bom*, Grzegorz Brozeló, Joanna Makowska”, Marek L. Kowalski”, Trine Thilsing*, Thomas Keil*'7, Paolo M. Matricardi"', Kjell Torén'?, Thibaut van Zele', Claus Bachert Barbara Rymarczyk'*, Christer Janson"*, Bertil Forsberg'7, Ewa Nizankowska-Mogilnicka's  and Peter G... Bumey'     Abstract  Background: Fruits and vegetables are rich in compounds with proposed antioxidant, antillergic and anti-inflam- matory properties, which could contribute to reduce the prevalence of asthma and allergic diseases.  Objective: We investigated the association between asthma, and chronic rhino-sinusitis (CRS) with intake of fruits and vegetables in European adults.  Methods: A stratiied random sample was drawn from the Global Alleray and Asthma Network of Excellence (GA2LEN) screening survey, in which 55,000 adults aged 15-75 answered a questionnaire on respiratory symptoms. Asthma score (derived from self-reported asthma symptoms) and CRS were the outcomes of interest. Dietary intake 0f 22 subgroups of fruits and vegetables vas ascertained using the intemationally validated GA?LEN Food Frequency Questionnaire. Adjusted associations were examined with negative binomial and multiple regressions. Simes proce dure was used to control for multiple testing.  Results: A total of 3206 individuals had valid data on asthma and dietary exposures ofinterest. 22.8% reported hav- ing at least 1 asthma symptom (asthma score > 1), whilst 19.5% had CRS. After adjustment for potential confounders, asthma score was negatively associated with intake of dried fruits (B-coefficient —2.34; 95% confidence interval [CI —4,09, —059), whilst CRS was statistically negatively associated with total intake of fruits (OR 0.73: 95% C10.55,097). Conversely, a positive association was observed benween asthma score and alliums vegetables (adjusted f-coeffcient 10,23;95% C1 0.06, 0.40). None of these associations remained statistically significant after controlling for multiple testing.  Conclusion and clinical relevance: There was no consistent evidence for an association of asthma or CRS with fruit and vegetable intake in this representative sample of European adults  Keywords: Fruits, Vegetables, Asthma, Chronic mino-sinusitis, Adults, Europe, Meta-analysis, GA?LEN        AConespondente: vgarcalasengimperialacuk " RespiatoryEpidenology, Occupational Medicine and PublicHealth Group, Natinal Heartand Lung Insítute, mperal Colege Lonon, Emmanuel Kaye Buldng. March 15,2013  New Food Allergies in a European Non-Mediterranean Region: Is Cannabis sativa to Blame?  D.G.Ebo® S.Swerts® V.Sabato® M.M.Hagendorens®® CH.Bridts®  P.G.Jorens® LS. De Clerck®  Departments of*Immunology, Allrgology and Rheumatology, >Pediatrics and “Clinical Pharmacology/Toxicology, Faculty of Medicine and Health Sciences, University of Antwerp and Antuwerp University Hospital, Antwerp, Blgium  Key Words Allergy - Basophil - Cannabis - Lipid transfer protein - Food - Specific IgE  Abstract  Background: Allergy to fruit and vegetables exhibit geo- graphic variation regarding the severity of symptoms and depending on the sensitization profile of the patient. These sensitization profiles and routes remain incompletely under- stood. Cannabis s a very popular drug and derived from Can- nabis sativa, a plant containing lipid transfer proteins (LTP) alsoknown asimportantallergensin plantand fruitallergies. In this study we sought to elucidate a potential connection between C.sativa allergy and plant food allergies. Methods: A case-control study involving 21 patients consulting for plant food allergies. Twelve patients were cannabis allergic and 9 had a pollen or latex allergy without cannabis allergy. Testing for cannabis IgE implied measurement of specific IgE, skin testing and basophl activation tests. Allergen com- ponentanalysis was performed with amicroarray technique. Results:Plant food allergy in patients with documented can- nabis allergy had more severe reactions than patients with- out cannabis allergy and frequently implied fruits and veg- etables that are not observed in a (birch) pollen-related food  syndrome. With the exception of 1 patient with cannabis al- lergy, all were sensitized to nonspecific (ns)-LTP. Conclusion: Our data suggest thatillicit cannabis abuse can result in can- nabis allergy with sensitization to ns-LTP. This sensitization might result in various plant-food allergies. Additional col- laborative studies in different geographical areas are need- ed to further elucidate on this hypothesis.  Copyrioht 20135, Karger AG,Sasel  Introduction  Allergy to fruits and vegetables is an important and evolving health issue [1] that is most frequently acquired via a direct sensitization over the gastrointestinal tract or a primary sensitization to pollen or to a lesser extent He- vea latex (2], Today, it appears that fruit and vegetable allergies exhibit geographic and age-related variation re- garding the severity of symptoms and depending on the sensitization profile of the patient. In Belgium, as in most other north European regions, plant food allergy in adults is generally characterized by an oral allergy syndrome (OAS) due o sensitization to the labile homologues of Bet v 1, the major allergen from birch (Betula verrucosa) pol- len [3-8].
